{"title_page": "Michael Herrick", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Michael Herrick\n|image=File:M J Herrick.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption=A portrait of Michael Herrick, painted by [[Eric Kennington]] in 1941\n|nickname=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1921|5|5|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], New Zealand\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1944|6|16|1921|5|5|df=yes}}\n|death_place= Denmark\n|placeofburial=\n|allegiance= New Zealand\n|branch= [[Royal  Air Force]]\n|serviceyears= 1939\u20131944{{KIA}}\n|rank= [[Squadron Leader]]\n|unit= \n|commands=[[No. 15 Squadron RNZAF]]\n|battles= [[Second World War]]\n*[[Battle of Britain]]\n*[[New Georgia campaign]]\n*[[Battle of the Treasury Islands]]\n|awards= [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] & [[medal bar|bar]]<br>[[Air Medal]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Michael Herrick''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DFC*}} (5 May 1921 \u2013 16 June 1944) was a New Zealand [[flying ace]] of the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) during the [[Second World War]]. He was credited with the destruction of eight enemy aircraft. \n\nBorn in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], New Zealand, Herrick joined the RAF in 1939. He flew [[Bristol Blenheim]]s on night operations with [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron]] during the [[Battle of Britain]], destroying three German bombers. He was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC) for his achievements during the battle. In late 1941, having shot down five enemy aircraft, he was sent to New Zealand on secondment to the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] to take command of its newly formed [[No. 15 Squadron RNZAF|No. 15 Squadron]]. With the squadron he flew two operational tours in the Pacific, including several missions around [[Guadalcanal]]. In 1944, having been awarded a [[medal bar|bar]] to his DFC, he returned to England to resume service with the RAF. He joined [[No. 305 Squadron RAF|No. 305 Squadron]], which operated the [[de Havilland Mosquito]] fighter-bomber, as one of its flight commanders. He was killed during a daylight raid on a German airfield at [[Aalborg]] in Denmark. In recognition of his services in the Pacific, he was posthumously awarded the United States [[Air Medal]].\n\n==Early life==\nMichael James Herrick was born in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]] in New Zealand on 5 May 1921, one of five boys of Edward Herrick and his wife, Ethne Rose.<ref name=NZH>{{cite web |last1=Phipps |first1=Gareth |title=Michael Herrick Biography |url=https://nzhistory.govt.nz/people/michael-herrick |website=New Zealand History |publisher=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CWGC/> He was educated at Hurworth School in Wanganui, before going onto Wanganui Collegiate School. While still at school, he took flying lessons and soon gained his pilots licence. In 1938, he gained a cadetship for the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF); he was to attend its [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell|college at Cranwell]] and travelled to England the following year to commence his training.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}}\n\n==Second World War==\nThe outbreak of the Second World War forced Herrick's cadetship, originally scheduled to run for two years, to be consolidated and he gained his wings in early 1940.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}} Commissioned as a [[pilot officer]] in March,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34841|date=19 March 1940|page=1637}}</ref> he was posted to [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron]] which was stationed at [[North Weald Airfield|North Weald]] and operated [[Bristol Blenheim]]s.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}} The squadron flew covering patrols for the ships evacuating the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] from [[Dunkirk]]. In June it began operating from [[RAF Martlesham Heath|Martlesham Heath]], flying convoy patrols and undertaking night operations.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=198}} \n\n===Battle of Britain===\n[[File:Bristol Blenheim - Martlesham - RAF Fighter Command 1940 HU104652.jpg|thumb|right|A Bristol Blenheim of No. 25 Squadron at Martlesham Heath, July 1940]]\nAlthough its aircraft had been intended for light bombing, No. 25 Squadron was in the process of converting to a night fighting role and the Blenheims were equipped with airborne radar.{{sfn|Claasen|2012|pp=153\u2013154}} This switch to a night fighting role coincided with an increase in nightly bombing raids mounted by the Germans.{{sfn|Thompson|1953|p=90}} On the night of 5 September, despite his aircraft's radar set malfunctioning, Herrick spotted a [[Heinkel He 111]] bomber caught in search lights and shot it down. Within minutes he repeated the feat, destroying a [[Dornier Do 17]] bomber and exhausting his ammunition.{{sfn|Claasen|2012|pp=153\u2013154}} For his exploit, he was later awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34951|date=24 September 1940|page=5655}}</ref> On 14 September, while flying a patrol north of [[London]], he was directed by his radar to another Heinkel He 111. Climbing up behind the bomber he opened fire, prompting its crew to jettison its bombload. As the German aircraft went down out of control and exploded but not before its rear gunner caused minor damage to Herrick's aircraft.{{sfn|Claasen|2012|pp=153\u2013154}} He had accounted for three of the four German aircraft destroyed by [[Fighter Command]] on night operations during September.{{sfn|Thompson|1953|p=90}} No. 25 Squadron shifted north in November, flying from [[RAF Wittering|Wittering]] and covering the [[Midlands|Midlands region]]. It began converting to [[Bristol Beaufighter]]s{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=198}} and by mid-1941 Herrick, now holding the rank of [[flying officer]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35158|date=9 May 1941|page=2671}}</ref> had destroyed a total of five German aircraft; his fifth, a [[Junkers Ju 88]], had been shot down in June 1941.{{sfn|Thompson|1953|p=134}}\n\n===Secondment===\nIn October 1941, Herrick was seconded to the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] (RNZAF){{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=198}} and by the end of the year was back in the country of his birth. He spent a period of time as an instructor at the No. 2 Flying Training School at [[RNZAF Base Woodbourne|Woodbourne]] and then [[RNZAF Base Ohakea|Ohakea]] before being posted to the RNZAF's [[No. 15 Squadron RNZAF|No. 15 Squadron]] in June 1942.<ref name=NZH/> The squadron had just been formed and, based at [[RNZAF Base Auckland|Whenuapai]], was training with [[Curtiss P-40 Warhawk|P-40 Kittyhawks]].{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=110}} \n\nAfter a few months it was sent to [[Tonga]], where it began operating aircraft, P40s, that had been recently used by the [[United States Army Air Force]]'s [[68th Fighter Squadron|No. 68 Pursuit Squadron]], with responsibility for the air defence of the island.{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=139\u2013140}} In February 1943, the squadron moved to [[Espiritu Santo]], the main island of [[Vanuatu]], assuming a similar defence role there for a few weeks before, in April, being dispatched to [[Guadalcanal]], in the [[Solomon Islands]]. Its role there was to carry out local patrols, fly escorts to bombers, and provide cover for American shipping convoys. By this time Herrick was commander of the squadron; its original commanding officer had been killed in a flying accident.<ref name=NZH/>{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=180\u2013181}} The squadron's initial encounter with the enemy took place on 6 May; while escorting a [[Lockheed Hudson]], Herrick and his wingman shared in the destruction of a Japanese float-plane.{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=181\u2013182}} This is acknowledged to be the first enemy aircraft shot down in the Pacific by fighters of the RNZAF.<ref name=NZH/> A few days later he took part in an escort mission, leading a flight of eight P-40s accompanying light bombers attacking Japanese destroyers and strafing landing craft.{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=181\u2013182}} On 7 June, he was involved in a large dogfight that took place when a force of over 100 Allied fighters, including twelve P-40s from No. 15 Squadron, encountered nearly around 50 Japanese [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]]es near the [[Russell Islands]]. On this occasion, Herrick shot down a Zero.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=184\u2013185}} \n\nIn late June, No. 15 Squadron completed its first operational tour and returned to New Zealand for a rest. It was back in Guadalcanal to commence its second tour in September, again flying escort to bombing missions and covering convoys. On 1 October, Herrick shared in the destruction of a [[Aichi D3A|Aichi D3A \"Val\"]] dive bomber that was attacking a convoy transporting troops of the [[3rd Division (New Zealand)|3rd New Zealand Division]] to [[Vella Lavella]]. Herrick's kill was one of seven Japanese aircraft shot down by the squadron that day.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=197}} In late October, No. 15 Squadron moved to Ondonga in [[New Georgia]];{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=200}} it was to support operations against the [[Treasury Islands]] and [[Bougainville Island|Bougainville]].{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=204}} \n\nOn 27 October, during the [[Battle of the Treasury Islands|landings at the Treasury Islands]] by New Zealand infantry and supporting troops, the squadron flew covering missions throughout the day. In doing so, they intercepted a force of 80 Japanese aircraft attempting to attack barges landing supplies and shot down four fighters, with Herrick accounting for one of them, a Zero.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=205}} The squadron also flew missions protecting the beachhead on Bougainville through out November. On one of these missions, Herrick was wounded in the foot during an attack on Japanese defensive positions. This would be his final sortie for he handed over command of the squadron and left to return to New Zealand.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=212}} In recognition of his services in the Solomons, Herrick was awarded a [[medal bar|bar]] to his DFC; this was gazetted in February 1944.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=36392|date=22 February 1944|supp=y|page=909}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the RAF===\nHerrick's stay in New Zealand was brief for his secondment to the RNZAF ended in December 1943 and the following month he embarked for England, via Canada, travelling on a troopship taking RNZAF personnel to [[Edmonton]] for flight training. Resuming his service with the RAF, he was sent to [[No. 305 Squadron RAF|No. 305 Squadron]], where he took command of one of its flights.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=201}} At the time of his joining the squadron, it operated [[de Havilland Mosquito]] fighter-bombers on nighttime missions to mainland Europe, targeting enemy airfields and launching sites for V1 rockets, but by the middle of the year it was also flying daytime operations. On 16 June 1944, Herrick and his Polish navigator flew a mission during the day to German-occupied Denmark, targeting a ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' airfield at [[Aalborg]]. They were accompanied by [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] [[John Braham (RAF officer)|John Braham]] in his own Mosquito, flying as a pair until Braham separated to pursue his target in [[Copenhagen]]. As Herrick approached the [[Jutland]] coast, his Mosquito was attacked by a [[Focke Wulf Fw 190]] flown by ''[[Leutnant]]'' Robert Spreckels. Although Herrick and his navigator bailed out when their aircraft was shot down, they were too low for their parachutes to open and were killed. Herrick landed in the sea and his body washed ashore two weeks later. Spreckels later shot down Braham, who became a prisoner of war. Interrogated by Spreckels, he was reportedly advised that Herrick had made a good account of himself before being shot down.<ref name=NZH/>{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=201}}\n\nHerrick is buried in the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]'s section of the [[Frederikshavn Cemetery]] in Denmark.<ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Herrick, Michael James |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2271241/herrick,-michael-james/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The month after his death, it was announced that he was to awarded the United States [[Air Medal]], in acknowledgement of his services in the Pacific; the medal was presented to his parents in a ceremony in [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]] in June 1945 by Captain Lloyd Gray, the [[Military attach\u00e9|Naval attache]] at the [[Embassy of the United States, Wellington|United States Embassy]]. The citation specifically noted his exploits in the Solomon Islands area during the period of May to June 1943.<ref>{{cite news |title=Great Record - Hastings Family: M. J. Herrick's Award |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/GISH19450615.2.87 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=Gisborne Herald |date=15 June 1945}}</ref>{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=202}} Two of his brothers also served in the RAF; both died on flying operations in the early years of the war.<ref name=NZH/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Claasen|first=Adam|title=Dogfight: The Battle of Britain|series=Anzac Battle Series|year=2012|publisher=Exisle Publishing|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=978-1-921497-28-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ross|first=J. M. S.|year=1955|title=Royal New Zealand Air Force|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2AirF.html|series=[[Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u201345]]|publisher=Historical Publications Branch|location=Wellington|oclc=912824475|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=H. L.|year=1953|title=New Zealanders with the Royal Air Force|volume=I|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2-1RAF.html|series=[[Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u201345]]|publisher=War History Branch|location=Wellington|oclc= \t270919916|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wynn |first1=Kenneth G. |title=A Clasp for 'The Few': New Zealanders with the Battle of Britain Clasp |date=1981 |publisher=Kenneth G. Wynn |location=Auckland, New Zealand |isbn=0-86-465-0256|ref=harv}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herrick, Michael}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hastings, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War II flying aces]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Michael Herrick\n|image=File:M J Herrick.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption=A portrait of Michael Herrick, painted by [[Eric Kennington]] in 1941\n|nickname=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1921|5|5|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], New Zealand\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1944|6|16|1921|5|5|df=yes}}\n|death_place= Denmark\n|placeofburial=\n|allegiance= New Zealand\n|branch= [[Royal  Air Force]]\n|serviceyears= 1939\u20131944{{KIA}}\n|rank= [[Squadron Leader]]\n|unit= \n|commands=[[No. 15 Squadron RNZAF]]\n|battles= [[Second World War]]\n*[[Battle of Britain]]\n*[[New Georgia campaign]]\n*[[Battle of the Treasury Islands]]\n|awards= [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] & [[medal bar|bar]]<br>[[Air Medal]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Michael Herrick''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|DFC*}} (5 May 1921 \u2013 16 June 1944) was a New Zealand [[flying ace]] of the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) during the [[Second World War]]. He was credited with the destruction of eight enemy aircraft. \n\nBorn in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], New Zealand, Herrick joined the RAF in 1939. He flew [[Bristol Blenheim]]s on night operations with [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron]] during the [[Battle of Britain]], destroying three German bombers. He was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC) for his achievements during the battle. In late 1941, having shot down five enemy aircraft, he was sent to New Zealand on secondment to the [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] to take command of its newly formed [[No. 15 Squadron RNZAF|No. 15 Squadron]]. With the squadron he flew two operational tours in the Pacific, including several missions around [[Guadalcanal]]. In 1944, having been awarded a [[medal bar|bar]] to his DFC, he returned to England to resume service with the RAF. He joined [[No. 305 Squadron RAF|No. 305 Squadron]], which operated the [[de Havilland Mosquito]] fighter-bomber, as one of its flight commanders. He was killed during a daylight raid on a German airfield at [[Aalborg]] in Denmark. In recognition of his services in the Pacific, he was posthumously awarded the United States [[Air Medal]].\n\n==Early life==\nMichael James Herrick was born in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]] in New Zealand on 5 May 1921, one of five boys of Edward Herrick and his wife, Ethne Rose.<ref name=NZH>{{cite web |last1=Phipps |first1=Gareth |title=Michael Herrick Biography |url=https://nzhistory.govt.nz/people/michael-herrick |website=New Zealand History |publisher=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CWGC/> He was educated at Hurworth School in Wanganui, before going onto Wanganui Collegiate School. While still at school, he took flying lessons and soon gained his pilots licence. In 1938, he gained a cadetship for the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF); he was to attend its [[Royal Air Force College Cranwell|college at Cranwell]] and travelled to England the following year to commence his training.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}}\n\n==Second World War==\nThe outbreak of the Second World War forced Herrick's cadetship, originally scheduled to run for two years, to be consolidated and he gained his wings in early 1940.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}} Commissioned as a [[pilot officer]] in March,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34841|date=19 March 1940|page=1637}}</ref> he was posted to [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron]] which was stationed at [[North Weald Airfield|North Weald]] and operated [[Bristol Blenheim]]s.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=197}} The squadron flew covering patrols for the ships evacuating the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] from [[Dunkirk]]. In June it began operating from [[RAF Martlesham Heath|Martlesham Heath]], flying convoy patrols and undertaking night operations.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=198}} \n\n===Battle of Britain===\n[[File:Bristol Blenheim - Martlesham - RAF Fighter Command 1940 HU104652.jpg|thumb|right|A Bristol Blenheim of No. 25 Squadron at Martlesham Heath, July 1940]]\nAlthough its aircraft had been intended for light bombing, No. 25 Squadron was in the process of converting to a night fighting role and the Blenheims were equipped with airborne radar.{{sfn|Claasen|2012|pp=153\u2013154}} This switch to a night fighting role coincided with an increase in nightly bombing raids mounted by the Germans.{{sfn|Thompson|1953|p=90}} On the night of 5 September, despite his aircraft's radar set malfunctioning, Herrick spotted a [[Heinkel He 111]] bomber caught in search lights and shot it down. Within minutes he repeated the feat, destroying a [[Dornier Do 17]] bomber and exhausting his ammunition.{{sfn|Claasen|2012|pp=153\u2013154}} For his exploit, he was later awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (DFC).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34951|date=24 September 1940|page=5655}}</ref> On 14 September, while flying a patrol north of [[London]], he was directed by his radar to another Heinkel He 111. Climbing up behind the bomber he opened fire, prompting its crew to jettison its bombload. As the German aircraft went down out of control and exploded but not before its rear gunner caused minor