r of the squadron; its original commanding officer had been killed in a flying accident.<ref name=NZH/>{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=180\u2013181}} The squadron's initial encounter with the enemy took place on 6 May; while escorting a [[Lockheed Hudson]], Herrick and his wingman shared in the destruction of a Japanese float-plane.{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=181\u2013182}} This is acknowledged to be the first enemy aircraft shot down in the Pacific by fighters of the RNZAF.<ref name=NZH/> A few days later he took part in an escort mission, leading a flight of eight P-40s accompanying light bombers attacking Japanese destroyers and strafing landing craft.{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=181\u2013182}} On 7 June, he was involved in a large dogfight that took place when a force of over 100 Allied fighters, including twelve P-40s from No. 15 Squadron, encountered nearly around 50 Japanese [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]]es near the [[Russell Islands]]. On this occasion, Herrick shot down a Zero.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|pp=184\u2013185}} \n\nIn late June, No. 15 Squadron completed its first operational tour and returned to New Zealand for a rest. It was back in Guadalcanal to commence its second tour in September, again flying escort to bombing missions and covering convoys. On 1 October, Herrick shared in the destruction of a [[Aichi D3A|Aichi D3A \"Val\"]] dive bomber that was attacking a convoy transporting troops of the [[3rd Division (New Zealand)|3rd New Zealand Division]] to [[Vella Lavella]]. Herrick's kill was one of seven Japanese aircraft shot down by the squadron that day.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=197}} In late October, No. 15 Squadron moved to Ondonga in [[New Georgia]];{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=200}} it was to support operations against the [[Treasury Islands]] and [[Bougainville]].{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=204}} \n\nOn 27 October, during the [[Battle of the Treasury Islands|landings at the Treasury Islands]] by New Zealand infantry and supporting troops, the squadron flew covering missions throughout the day. In doing so, they intercepted a force of 80 Japanese aircraft attempting to attack barges landing supplies and shot down four fighters, with Herrick accounting for one of them, a Zero.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=205}} The squadron also flew missions protecting the beachhead on Bougainville through out November. On one of these missions, Herrick was wounded in the foot during an attack on Japanese defensive positions. This would be his final sortie for he handed over command of the squadron and left to return to New Zealand.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=200}}{{sfn|Ross|1955|p=212}} In recognition of his services in the Solomons, Herrick was awarded a [[medal bar|bar]] to his DFC; this was gazetted in February 1944.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=36392|date=22 February 1944|supp=y|page=909}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the RAF===\nHerrick's stay in New Zealand was brief for his secondment to the RNZAF ended in December 1943 and the following month he embarked for England, via Canada, travelling on a troopship taking RNZAF personnel to [[Edmonton]] for flight training. Resuming his service with the RAF, he was sent to [[No. 305 Squadron RAF|No. 305 Squadron]], where he took command of one of its flights.{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=201}} At the time of his joining the squadron, it operated [[de Havilland Mosquito]] fighter-bombers on nighttime missions to mainland Europe, targeting enemy airfields and launching sites for V1 rockets, but by the middle of the year it was also flying daytime operations. On 16 June 1944, Herrick and his Polish navigator flew a mission during the day to German-occupied Denmark, targeting a ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' airfield at [[Aalborg]]. They were accompanied by [[Wing Commander]] [[John Braham (RAF officer)|John Braham]] in his own Mosquito, flying as a pair until Braham separated to pursue his target in [[Copenhagen]]. As Herrick approached the [[Jutland]] coast, his Mosquito was attacked by a [[Focke Wulf Fw 190]] flown by ''[[Leutnant]]'' Robert Spreckels. Although Herrick and his navigator bailed out when their aircraft was shot down, they were too low for their parachutes to open and were killed. Herrick landed in the sea and his body washed ashore two weeks later. Spreckels later shot down Braham, who became a prisoner of war. Interrogated by Spreckels, he was reportedly advised that Herrick had made a good account of himself before being shot down.<ref name=NZH/>{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=201}}\n\nHerrick is buried in the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]'s section of the [[Frederikshavn Cemetery]] in Denmark.<ref name=CWGC>{{cite web |title=Casualty Record: Herrick, Michael James |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2271241/herrick,-michael-james/ |publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> The month after his death, it was announced that he was to awarded the United States [[Air Medal]], in acknowledgement of his services in the Pacific; the medal was presented to his parents in a ceremony in [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]] in June 1945 by Captain Lloyd Gray, the [[Military attach\u00e9|Naval attache]] at the [[Embassy of the United States, Wellington|United States Embassy]]. The citation specifically noted his exploits in the Solomon Islands area during the period of May to June 1943.<ref>{{cite news |title=Great Record - Hastings Family: M. J. Herrick's Award |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/GISH19450615.2.87 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=Gisborne Herald |date=15 June 1945}}</ref>{{sfn|Wynn|1981|p=202}} Two of his brothers also served in the RAF; both died on flying operations in the early years of the war.<ref name=NZH/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Claasen|first=Adam|title=Dogfight: The Battle of Britain|series=Anzac Battle Series|year=2012|publisher=Exisle Publishing|location=Auckland, New Zealand|isbn=978-1-921497-28-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ross|first=J. M. S.|year=1955|title=Royal New Zealand Air Force|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2AirF.html|series=[[Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u201345]]|publisher=Historical Publications Branch|location=Wellington|oclc=912824475|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=H. L.|year=1953|title=New Zealanders with the Royal Air Force|volume=I|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2-1RAF.html|series=[[Official History of New Zealand in the Second World War 1939\u201345]]|publisher=War History Branch|location=Wellington|oclc= \t270919916|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wynn |first1=Kenneth G. |title=A Clasp for 'The Few': New Zealanders with the Battle of Britain Clasp |date=1981 |publisher=Kenneth G. Wynn |location=Auckland, New Zealand |isbn=0-86-465-0256|ref=harv}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herrick, Michael}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hastings, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War II flying aces]]\n[[Category:New Zealand World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Bougainville\u2192Bougainville Island,Wing Commander\u2192Wing commander (rank)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Herrick"}
{"title_page": "Bude\u0219ti", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County\n|official_name=Bude\u0219ti\n|other_name = Budeshti\n|image_shield=\n|image_map=Budesti jud Calarasi.png\n|leader_name=Dumitru Iorgu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=UNPR\n|area_total_km2=93\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|13|48|N|26|27|0|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n'''Bude\u0219ti''' ([[Romani language|Romani]]: ''Budeshti'') is a small provincial town in [[C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County]], approximately 30&nbsp;km (20 miles) south-east of [[Bucharest]], the capital of [[Romania]]. Three villages are administered by the town: Aprozi, Buciumeni and Gruiu. Bude\u0219ti was the birthplace of famous Romanian violin player [[Ion Voicu]]. It has a population of 7,024 people. Near Bude\u0219ti, the [[D\u00e2mbovi\u021ba (river)|D\u00e2mbovi\u021ba]] flows into the [[Arge\u0219 (river)|Arge\u0219]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |10044\n|2002 |9596\n|2011 |7024\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, Bude\u0219ti is the Romanian town with the largest proportion of [[Romani people|Romani]]. As one of two urban areas where Romani make up more than 20% of the total population, Bude\u0219ti is also the one of two towns in Romania where the [[Romani language]] has co-official status alongside [[Romanian language|Romanian]], with education, signage and public service provided in both languages. 62% of the town's population is of [[Romanians|Romanian ethnicity]] and 37.8% is of Romani ethnicity.\n\nIn terms of religion, 99.59% of the population declared themselves to be [[Romanian Orthodox]] at the 2002 census, 0.28% were [[Pentecostal]], and 0.11% declared another religion.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns in Romania with large Roma populations]]\n* [[Roma minority in Romania]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bude\u0219ti}}\n* [http://www.calarasi.insse.ro/cmscalarasi/rw/resource/date_provizorii_rpl_2011.pdf?view=true 2011 census data for Bude\u0219ti]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Budesti}}\n[[Category:Populated places in C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romani communities in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County\n|official_name=Bude\u0219ti\n|other_name = Budeshti\n|image_shield=\n|image_map=Budesti jud Calarasi.png\n|leader_name=Dumitru Iorgu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=UNPR\n|area_total_km2=93\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|13|48|N|26|27|0|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n'''Bude\u0219ti''' ([[Romani language|Romani]]: ''Budeshti'') is a small provincial town in [[C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County]], approximately 30&nbsp;km (20 miles) south-east of [[Bucharest]], the capital of [[Romania]]. Three villages are administered by the town: Aprozi, Buciumeni and Gruiu. Bude\u0219ti was the birthplace of famous Romanian violin player [[Ion Voicu]]. It has a population of 7,024 people. Near Bude\u0219ti, the [[D\u00e2mbovi\u021ba (river)|D\u00e2mbovi\u021ba]] flows into the [[Arge\u0219 (river)|Arge\u0219]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |10044\n|2002 |9596\n|2011 |7024\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, Bude\u0219ti is the Romanian town with the largest proportion of [[Romani people|Romani]]. As one of two urban areas where Romani make up more than 20% of the total population, Bude\u0219ti is also the one of two towns in Romania where the [[Romani language]] has co-official status alongside [[Romanian language|Romanian]], with education, signage and public service provided in both languages. 62% of the town's population is of [[Romanians|Romanian ethnicity]] and 37.8% is of Romani ethnicity.\n\nIn terms of religion, 99.59% of the population declared themselves to be [[Romanian Orthodox]] at the 2002 census, 0.28% were [[Pentecostal]], and 0.11% declared another religion.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns in Romania with large Roma populations]]\n* [[Roma minority in Romania]]\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bude\u0219ti}}\n* [http://www.calarasi.insse.ro/cmscalarasi/rw/resource/date_provizorii_rpl_2011.pdf?view=true 2011 census data for Bude\u0219ti]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Budesti}}\n[[Category:Populated places in C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romani communities in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bude%C8%99ti"}
{"title_page": "S\u00e2ntana", "text_new": "{{about|the town in Arad County|the commune in Mure\u0219 County|S\u00e2ntana de Mure\u0219|other uses|Santana (disambiguation)}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Arad\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_skyline=Kirchejesu.jpg\n|map_caption = Location of S\u00e2ntana\n|official_name=S\u00e2ntana\n|image_shield=\n|image_map=Santana jud Arad.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|46|21|N|21|30|E|display=it|region:RO_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n|leader_name= Daniel-Sorin Tomu\u021ba<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=\n|website=\n}}\n\n'''S\u00e2ntana''' ({{IPA-ro|s\u0268n\u02c8tana}}; {{lang-de|Neusanktanna}}; {{lang-hu|\u00dajszentanna}}) is a town in north-western [[Romania]], in the county of [[Arad County|Arad]]. It had 12,936 inhabitants as of 2002. The town is situated in the northern part of the Aradului Plateau, at a 29&nbsp;km distance from the county capital ([[Arad, Romania|Arad]]). Declared a town in 2003, it administers one village, Caporal Alexa (''Erd\u0151skerek'').\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|2002 |12936\n|2011 |10725\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census the population of the town counts 10725 inhabitants. From an ethnic point of view it has the following structure: 84.89% are Romanians, 9.57% Roma, 3.14% Germans, 2.07% Hungarians and 0.4% are of other or undeclared nationalities. 79.6% are [[Romanian Orthodox]], 11.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 5.5% [[Roman Catholic]] and 1.2% [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]].\n\n==History==\nThe first documentary record of the locality under the name S\u00e2ntana goes back to the year 1828. The settlement is the\nresult of the continuous development of Coml\u0103u\u0219, a locality mentioned already in 1334. Caporal Alexa was mentioned in\n1334 when it was called Kerecton. Until 1926, it was called Cherechiu, which is still its colloquial name.\n\n==Economy==\nAlthough the economy of the town is prevalent agricultural, the secondary and tertiary economic sectors have also developed\nrecently. S\u00e2ntana is an important centre of vineyards.\n\n==Tourism==\nIts status as a significant road and railway junction can be used also for the promotion and improvement of the tourism.\nThe specific architecture, the historical and architectural monuments as the \"Convictului\" building, the copyhold house and the fortifications called \"Cetatea veche\" are only a few of the locality's touristic sights.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|S\u00e2ntana}}\n\n{{LocalitiesArad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santana}}\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Arad County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Cri\u0219ana]]\n[[Category:Former Danube Swabian communities in Romania]]\n\n\n{{Arad-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the town in Arad County|the commune in Mure\u0219 County|S\u00e2ntana de Mure\u0219|other uses|Santana (disambiguation)}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Arad\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_skyline=Kirchejesu.jpg\n|map_caption = Location of S\u00e2ntana\n|official_name=S\u00e2ntana\n|image_shield=\n|image_map=Santana jud Arad.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|46|21|N|21|30|E|display=it|region:RO_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n|leader_name= Daniel-Sorin Tomu\u021ba<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=\n|website=\n}}\n\n'''S\u00e2ntana''' ({{IPA-ro|s\u0268n\u02c8tana}}; {{lang-de|Neusanktanna}}; {{lang-hu|\u00dajszentanna}}) is a town in north-western [[Romania]], in the county of [[Arad County|Arad]]. It had 12,936 inhabitants as of 2002. The town is situated in the northern part of the Aradului Plateau, at a 29&nbsp;km distance from the county capital ([[Arad, Romania|Arad]]). Declared a town in 2003, it administers one village, Caporal Alexa (''Erd\u0151skerek'').\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|2002 |12936\n|2011 |10725\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census the population of the town counts 10725 inhabitants. From an ethnic point of view it has the following structure: 84.89% are Romanians, 9.57% Roma, 3.14% Germans, 2.07% Hungarians and 0.4% are of other or undeclared nationalities. 79.6% are [[Romanian Orthodox]], 11.5% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 5.5% [[Roman Catholic]] and 1.2% [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]].\n\n==History==\nThe first documentary record of the locality under the name S\u00e2ntana goes back to the year 1828. The settlement is the\nresult of the continuous development of Coml\u0103u\u0219, a locality mentioned already in 1334. Caporal Alexa was mentioned in\n1334 when it was called Kerecton. Until 1926, it was called Cherechiu, which is still its colloquial name.\n\n==Economy==\nAlthough the economy of the town is prevalent agricultural, the secondary and tertiary economic sectors have also developed\nrecently. S\u00e2ntana is an important centre of vineyards.\n\n==Tourism==\nIts status as a significant road and railway junction can be used also for the promotion and improvement of the tourism.\nThe specific architecture, the historical and architectural monuments as the \"Convictului\" building, the copyhold house and the fortifications called \"Cetatea veche\" are only a few of the locality's touristic sights.\n\n{{commons category|S\u00e2ntana}}\n\n{{LocalitiesArad}}\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santana}}\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Arad County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Cri\u0219ana]]\n[[Category:Former Danube Swabian communities in Romania]]\n\n{{Arad-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A2ntana"}
